== css - wiki book index ==
* see screenshot provided (non-blocking)
* page: [[copy.fail]]
* bug: weird word wrapping
* bug: uneven symbol alignment

'''DEV'''
* This is actually a general conceptual problem, which admin has to decide on.
** The less space there is, the less chance for accurate display of the text. Especially if the buttons have to stay horizontal (side by side) instead of vertical
** The text is always a problem, because although there is auto-hyphenation in CSS, browser won't touch proper names. The will never separate "Who- \n nix" for example. Also they won't separate "Documentation", but they will "documentation". The uppercase is a warning to them that this might be a proper name. There is an option to add "soft hyphens" manually. But as we auto-generate our words here, we cannot manually add the hyphens (we could but I can only think of a complex solution)
* Possible solutions
*# Everything stays the same, but if it's too small then the text will be auto-hidden "...", so it will always be just one line of text. In this solution I would also have screen thresholds where the font gets smaller for smaller screens
*# We could put the buttons vertically if they cross a certain screen width threshold (small screens). Problem here still: The words could be too long before the threshold is even reached
*# A combination of 1 and 2 might be, that for normal screens the text will definitely just be on one line (overflow will be hidden with "..."). And under a certain thereshold the buttons will be vertical instead of horizontal

